```yaml
# Strategic scope — used by /matrix to evaluate spec fit (Spec 110)
# Defines what this project IS and IS NOT. /matrix classifies draft specs
# as on-mission, borderline, or scope-creep based on this definition.
# If absent, /matrix infers scope from CLAUDE.md project description.
forge.strategic_scope: |
  This project is a spec-driven development workflow template.
  Core loop: spec → implement → close → learn (with evidence gates).
  In scope: spec lifecycle, gates, evidence capture, process enforcement,
  signal-driven improvement, template bootstrapping via Copier.
  Out of scope: runtime infrastructure (scheduling, dispatch — that's NanoClaw),
  code analysis engines (that's MCP servers), IDE extensions or web apps
  (those are separate products), AI model features (those are upstream).
```

```yaml
# Session context briefing — controls /now "Last time on [project]" section (Spec 105)
# When true (default), /now reads recent session logs, signals, and scratchpad
# to provide a continuity brief at session start. Set false to skip.
forge.context.session_briefing: true
```

```yaml
# Context optimization — controls automatic compaction behavior (Spec 256)
# Reduces token costs in long sessions by compacting context at natural transition points.
#
# Tiers:
#   minimal   — No auto-compaction. Standard verbose output. Current default behavior.
#                Best for: short sessions, debugging, when you need full context history.
#                Trade-off: highest token cost in long multi-spec sessions.
#
#   balanced  — Auto-compact after /close when context exceeds compact_threshold_pct.
#                Standard output verbosity preserved. Compaction only at natural transitions.
#                Best for: typical multi-spec sessions where cost matters but output quality is priority.
#                Trade-off: brief pause after /close when compaction triggers; recent context summarized.
#
#   aggressive — Auto-compact after /close (always, regardless of threshold).
#                Reduced output verbosity: shorter section headers, compressed tables, abbreviated labels.
#                Best for: rapid multi-spec sprints, cost-sensitive environments, high-volume batch work.
#                Trade-off: terser output may omit context helpful for human review; frequent compaction
#                pauses; reduced output may make /close Review Briefs harder to scan.
#
# compact_threshold_pct: percentage of model context window that triggers compaction.
#   Only applies to balanced tier (aggressive always compacts).
#   Default: 60. Range: 10-90. Lower = more frequent compaction, higher = less frequent.
#
# Note: compaction NEVER fires mid-command. It only triggers at natural transition points
# (after /close completes). Active spec work (/implement, /close, /review) is never interrupted.
# Information required for AC verification at /close is never removed by compaction.
forge.context.optimization:
  level: minimal                  # minimal | balanced | aggressive
  compact_threshold_pct: 60       # percentage of context window that triggers compaction (balanced only)
```

